rComments: Awful handwriting. Never post notes. A lot to memorize.

Prof. Adams is one of the GOAT profs. Great lectures, interesting stories, and accessible. The course is very difficult on its own. The exams are fair but a few questions require you to think outside the box, so it is harder to achieve higher than 80% than your typical course.

he has good ratings, but I think he's just average. he explains the material fairly well, but makes the exams much harder than they need to be to test us on the material. Imagine only being taught how to take derivatives of a function, but having to know how to integrate on the exam. This is basically that class.

if you wouldn't describe yourself as smarter than say 80% of the other students in your program, avoid this course. You might fail it The content is important, and hes a great lecturer. The exams are hard because the questions expect you to understand the material insde and out so that you can apply it. CSI3105 is easy in comparison.

The prof is kind and caring to students. His lecture is really good. However his course notes are not well-organized. There is not a clear hierarchy among the stuff. His amazing handwriting which is like a bunch of cipher text reflects perfectly that he's a security/cryptography professor.

Carlisle Adam's is one of the best professors. He has so much experience and knowledge. He is also so hard working. His lectures are very much interesting. Worth taking his course. Don't miss out if you really want to learn something in your Degree.

Might actually be the greatest prof in the faculty. You can clearly see that he has a whole career's worth of experience behind him when he teaches. The lectures and material are really interesting if you like cybersecurity, and the workload isn't particularly heavy (lots of memorization though) so it makes for a nice elective.

Not allowed to miss more than 2 classes. Prof is amazing. Course content is awesome but 'insanely' difficult. Intensive reading is required even for the assignments. Every single class and every single word spoken is important. Read the notes thoroughly. Research online (wiki) and refer at least 3-4 books in the course outline. Then go.. read again

The best prof I ever had. Very inspiring, clear. The Computer Security course is well organized and really interesting. I would take it again! Textbook not used. Assignments and labs were easy, exams are theoretical and close to the material.

Great prof who taught the course (crypto) in a very interesting way. Has real world experience and lots of cool stories that I won't spoil. Some people found the exams hard, but I thought they were straightforward if you understand the concepts well enough to think your way through some slightly novel scenarios. Tons of fun, definitely recommend!

Best prof you could ever have at the University of Ottawa. One of the few profs who worked in industry before teaching. He is very knowledgeable on the topics he teaches and has stories for many of them which makes the class interesting. He cares a lot about his students. I highly recommend taking any class with him if you have the chance.

All his courses are well structured and organized. He covers every topic in detail. For the finals, he will give some papers to study which is the only hard work in the course. Besides he is a good human being, replies to all queries asked and gives a good feedback. All the questions in the final exam are covered from class notes. Best professor.

He is one of the best professor in the university. His courses are terrific and he puts stress on student learning. His course is not tough. All you have to do is to read the study material thoroughly. Exams are not tough but conceptual. Every thing covered in the exam will be from from his notes. Overall he is an amazing person and wonderful prof.

Very interesting Prof. One of the few profs who worked in industry before teaching. He is very knowledgeable on the topics he teaches and has stories for many of them which makes the class interesting. If you pay attention in class and take notes, you'll be fine. He usually asks big picture questions on his exams.

I had him twice as my prof in two different classes. he has a monotonous voice, so lecture might sound boring but he is very knowledgeable. the course (csi4139) had a lot of materials, but they were presented in an organized way. the labs and assignments required a lot of work, but very useful. the exams are hard and has an unusual marking scheme
teacherRatingTags: ['Lots of homework', 'Get ready to read', 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: Easy course. For presentation, dress and speak professionally without stuttering while looking at the audience; don't over-"decorate" the slides. Lots of slides, but he tells which ones to focus for the final. For report, choose an easy topic before it gets selected and disappears from the online list.  Attend the classes as not all slides are easy

One of the best prof and one of the best course in CSI. He is extremely knowledgeable as he is the designer of CAST, one of the contenders for AES. The course is very interesting and you will learn a lot. You will have to take notes constantly. The will be some group/ring/field maths involved. Midterm and final are hard, so be careful.
Do Take the course if ur not an Expert on the topic . He fails many people in his final exam ..!
DO NOT TAKE THE COURSE IF U CAN'T CLEAR THE FINAL TEST NOT WORTH THE EFFORT

He'll tell you to refer lecture notes for finals but exam questions will reflect stuff from other planets. There is a level of toughness that you prepare for any exam but professor adams will cross that level to make your life difficult in the finals. Trust me, if you don't drop the course at the right time you will definitely suffer in the end.

Excellent professor. Good teaching style. Some lectures were quite inspirational and thought provoking.  Course material was well organized. Course load was manageable. assignments were quite easy. A little extra effort required for final. As long as you go through all lectures and all reading material you'll pass with good grades.

He is a great knowlegable Prof. But he wont mind to kill a student by failing the student. His way of writing on the board, very small font is very cumbersum on students. But he will answer your questiion upto the satisfaction. His marking scheme is a bit tough. I like him as a Prof and as a person of ideology.

Professor Adams is a very calm and mellowed-out kind of guy. I really enjoyed the course ELG2911 with him, despite alot of assignments. (they were really easy though) We had no midterm in the course. If you do the assignments well and on time you will do very well in the course. I'm pretty sure that the class average was around A-

In university I found that there are two types of profs a teacher, and a lecturer. The teacher explains the concepts you are supposed to know. The lecturer will discuss applications, limitiations, extensions, and maybe give a few examples. He assumes that you can learn from the book. This is not to say which type is better. Adams is a lecturer.

A great professor. You really need to understand the book, attend classes, and do all the labs in order to do well in the course. For me this was a hard course, the load was very high but definitely an enjoyable one.

Don't be fooled by other rating. He can't even produce the slides. The whole term were blackboad copying, 10 pages a day. For him, knowldedge == wisdom. Just remember stuffs will make you wise.  A hardrive is better than him. He can bore you to death.  btw, his marking is way too hash. Beaten down a student doesn't make him look smart.

Delivered the (large amounts of) material in an organized and clear way. The 2 assignments (theory, papers) and 3 labs (practical, Java implementations of the theory) were way above my average work load, but not impossibly hard. Take every mark possible from them because the exams are difficult. Also take good class notes (laptop), you'll need them
Yeah, he's a good professor.
Excellent Prof. Knowledgeable. One of the few profs in ottawa u who has some significant contribution in his field. Look up CAST encryption!!
Great Prof! one of the best in Ottawa U.
